        "closed_date": 1358098469,
        "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/868368/what-can-i-use-to-create-a-rest-client-in-java",
        "last_activity_date": 1358081358,
        "creation_date": 1242390040,
        "answer_count": 7,
        "title": "What can I use to create a REST client in Java?",
        "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Possible Duplicate:<\/strong><br>\n  <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/221442/rest-clients-for-java\">Rest clients for Java?<\/a>  <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n\n\n<p>If I want to use Java to create a REST client, what should I use?<\/p>\n\n<p>Can i use CXF?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 868368,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "rest",
            "cxf"
        ],
        "score": 6,
        "accepted_answer_id": 868416,
        "closed_reason": "exact duplicate",
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 16234,
        "last_edit_date": 1495541158
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c53d539b59c19087182f0b1c53bb52de?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 7450,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 12960,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12960/brian-agnew",
                "reputation": 273383,
                "display_name": "Brian Agnew"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1343524666,
            "creation_date": 1242390816,
            "body": "<p>There is a <a href=\"http://blogs.oracle.com/sandoz/entry/jersey_client_api\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Jersey client API<\/a> that allows you to easily implement clients in Java<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868430,
            "question_id": 868368,
            "last_edit_date": 1343524666
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/wA6mv.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 2096,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2890,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2890/vinnie",
                "reputation": 12801,
                "display_name": "Vinnie",
                "accept_rate": 80
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1242391767,
            "creation_date": 1242391767,
            "body": "<p>I used <a href=\"http://www.restlet.org/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Restlet<\/a>.  I really liked it and wrote <a href=\"http://vincentfazio.blogspot.com/2007/10/restlet.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">a blog post<\/a> about my experience.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868495,
            "question_id": 868368
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/tGVIt.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2842,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4023,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4023/matthew-murdoch",
                "reputation": 31641,
                "display_name": "Matthew Murdoch",
                "accept_rate": 89
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1242458548,
            "creation_date": 1242390669,
            "body": "<p>I've had success using <a href=\"http://hc.apache.org/httpclient-3.x/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">HttpClient<\/a> from Jakarta Commons.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also Java comes with <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5.0/docs/api/java/net/HttpURLConnection.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">URLConnection<\/a> but you might want to look at <a href=\"http://www.innovation.ch/java/HTTPClient/urlcon_vs_httpclient.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this comparison<\/a> with <a href=\"http://hc.apache.org/httpclient-3.x/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">HttpClient<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://cxf.apache.org/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Apache CXF<\/a> does support REST clients (see <a href=\"http://cwiki.apache.org/CXF20DOC/jax-rs.html#JAX-RS-ClientAPI\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here<\/a>) but seems like overkill (CXF is a general 'services' framework and therefore complicated with support for CORBA, SOAP etc.)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868416,
            "question_id": 868368,
            "last_edit_date": 1242458548
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/eea9722b47ea662beb64100f720ec952?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 32546,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 90393,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/90393/kingink",
                "reputation": 536,
                "display_name": "KingInk"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1242421951,
            "creation_date": 1242421951,
            "body": "<p>imo there is hardly a need for a framework, simply use the servlet API and implement the request methods you need aka POST / GET / PUT / DELETE / HEAD<\/p>\n\n<p>an example: <a href=\"http://www.exampledepot.com/egs/javax.servlet/com_mycompany_MyServlet.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://www.exampledepot.com/egs/javax.servlet/com_mycompany_MyServlet.html<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 870898,
            "question_id": 868368
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/60adb60c59462ef0cb9db65853736cf4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 30670,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 83741,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/83741/alexander-torstling",
                "reputation": 18988,
                "display_name": "Alexander Torstling",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1242422912,
            "creation_date": 1242422912,
            "body": "<p>I think it really depends on the app and your environment, but I find <a href=\"http://www.jboss.org/resteasy/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">resteasy<\/a> really easy (since it is so declarative) and configurable. See <a href=\"http://www.jboss.org/file-access/default/members/resteasy/freezone/docs/1.1-RC2/userguide/html_single/index.html#RESTEasy_Client_Framework\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">chapter 30<\/a> for the client documentation.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 870946,
            "question_id": 868368
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3837ba41452ec90dd5ebf15e56be556d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 100041,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 269868,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/269868/atanas-roussev",
                "reputation": 61,
                "display_name": "Atanas Roussev"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269674361,
            "creation_date": 1269674361,
            "body": "<p>Use <a href=\"http://www.roussev.org/eclipse-rest-http-client-plugin-http4e/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">HTTP4e REST client<\/a> add-on for Eclipse. It is simple to use and has Java/C#/Ruby/Flex/ActionScript/etc.. one click code generation.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2528498,
            "question_id": 868368
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/XqJna.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1050968,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1054925,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1054925/r-jana",
                "reputation": 1138,
                "display_name": "R-JANA",
                "accept_rate": 64
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1348751235,
            "creation_date": 1348751235,
            "body": "<p>I tried using examples given in this ling <a href=\"http://cxf.apache.org/docs/jax-rs-client-api.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://cxf.apache.org/docs/jax-rs-client-api.html<\/a>\nI faced the problem that the Interface or the Impl may not be always avilable to client side to generate proxy. \nI also tried wadl2java to see if clients are generated. CXF 2.6 version did not create client class.<\/p>\n\n<p>I am happy with HTTPclient call till some concrete implementation changes ways to write client.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note: We are using only CXF with Java thus only experimenting with CXF. other implementation may give different results<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12622133,
            "question_id": 868368
        }
    ],
